tutaj jest dockerfile dla kontenera ktory zwiera moje wersje pHierCC i scipy, ktory jest tak kompilowany by klastrowanie hierarchinczne single linkage 
szlo na macierzy z typem danych short (odpowiadajace np.int16) co jest wystarczajace dla cgMLST ktorego max odleglosc nie moze wyniesc wiecej niz 
liczba alleli w schemacie tj. dla chmlst salmonelli 3200 a int16 akceptuje poprawnie wartosci do bodajce 300 000

skopiowano wersje skryptow z all_speed_test_3 i probuje zmienic clastrowanie "complete" aby rowniez akceptowalo macierz short 


On 2026-03-04 we diagnosed recurring failures in the weekly pHierCC clustering job (run via SCRON/Slurm and Docker) that had previously worked for months without changes to the container image. The job failed during the single-linkage run with `OSError: [Errno 24] Too many open files`, and a later `dist1.npy` missing-file error was only a downstream consequence of that first failure.

The root cause was a low file descriptor limit (`nofile`) propagated into the Slurm job environment (`PropagateResourceLimits=ALL`). In our scheduled job, the shell started with `soft nofile=1024` (hard `131072`), and because `docker run` was executed without an explicit `--ulimit`, the container inherited the same low soft limit. pHierCC creates a large multiprocessing pool, which exhausted file descriptors and crashed. This was confirmed by tests showing that `sbatch --propagate=NONE` raised the job limit and that the same container worked when run with a higher explicit `nofile` limit.

As a temporary hardcoded workaround, we added `--ulimit nofile=262144:262144` to each `docker run` command in the clustering script. This restored successful execution under Slurm/SCRON. We also recommend keeping `set -euo pipefail` in the wrapper/scripts so the workflow stops immediately on the first failure instead of continuing to later steps with missing intermediate files.
